frameDefinitions: This frame is concerned with the idea that people (Participant_1, Participant_2, or Participants) participate in an organized, rule-governed activity (the Competition) in order to achieve some advantageous outcome (often the Prize).

This frame consists of words that describe a hostile encounter between opposing forces (Side_1 and Side_2, collectively conceptualizable as Sides) over a disputed Issue and/or in order to reach a specific  Purpose. '' 'He still wants to fight Mike Tyson in about 8 months.'
A group of Arguers (also expressible as Arguer1 and Arguer2) express incompatible opinions or beliefs about an Issue.
Words in this frame have to do with a Cognizer creating a new intellectual entity, the Idea.
A physical entity, construed as a point-Sound_source, emits a Sound.
Geography as defined by its use.
frameExamples: He still wants to <t>fight</t> Mike Tyson in about 8 months.
We <t>bickered</t> about semantics for an hour.
I 've been trying to <t>come up</t> with a plan .
You must land in the next <t><fex name='Locale'>airfield</fex></t>, as this one is currently having difficulties.

Cognizer is the person who comes up with or conceptualizes the Invention. It is normally expressed as an External Argument: 

<fex name='Cognizer'>Kim</fex> <t>devised</t> a new recipe.
Invention is the intellectual creation of the Cognizer. It is normally expressed as an NP Object, but sometimes as a PP Complement:
The <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Idea</fen> is created.
The location in which the <fen>Cognizer</fen> comes up with the <fen>Idea</fen>.

The frame element <fen>Sound_source</fen> is assigned to a constituent referring to a physical entity which emits a sound. Such an entity must have an appropriately complex internal structure such that it can create a sound. For example, a machine or some other thing with moving parts can create sound by itself.

The frame element <fen>Sound</fen> is incorporated in the meaning of the verbs of this frame. Otherwise, this role is assigned to NPs which actually refer to a sound in the presence of the target. This typically occurs when the target is a verb used as a modifier in its <ment>-ing</ment> form, e.g.:
An event in which one or more <fen>Sound_source</fen>s participate and which is accompanied by <fen>Sound</fen>.
The time when the <fen>Noisy_event</fen> occurs.

The location of the <fen>Sound_source</fen>. This role differs from <fen>Location_of_source</fen> only in terms of point of view; the latter role implies a point of view that is not on the <fen>Sound_source</fen>.
A stable bounded area.  It is typically the designation of the nouns of Locale-derived frames.
The activity that is carried out in the <fen>Locale</fen>.
